<section><title>solution: multipathing</title>
	<para>1. Find a partner and decide who will be iSCSI Target and who will be iSCSI Initiator and Multipather. Set up Multipath as we did in the theory.</para>
	<screen>Look in the theory...</screen>
	<para>2. Uncomment the big 'defaults' section in /etc/multipath.conf and disable friendly names. Verify that multipath can work. You may need to check the manual for <command>/lib/dev/scsi_id</command> and for <command>multipath.conf</command>.</para>
	<screen>vi multipath.conf</screen>
	<screen>remove # for the big defaults section
add # for the very small one with friendly_names active
add the --replace-whitespace option to scsi_id.

defaults {
        udev_dir                /dev
        polling_interval        10
        path_selector           "round-robin 0"
        path_grouping_policy    multibus
        getuid_callout          "/lib/udev/scsi_id --whitelisted --replace\
-whitespace --device=/dev/%n"
        prio                    const
        path_checker            readsector0
        rr_min_io               100
        max_fds                 8192
        rr_weight               priorities
        failback                immediate
        no_path_retry           fail
        user_friendly_names     no
}</screen>
